        {
            "id": "aa4018b3516547bc9729c",
            "questionText": "A kettle contains $!$1.5$!$ liters of water initially at $!$25^\\text{o}C$!$. Calculate the total energy, in joules, required to heat the water to its boiling point ($!$100^\\text{o}C$!$) and completely convert it into steam. Assume the density of water is $!$1 \\, kg/L$!$, the specific heat capacity of water is $!$4.18 \\, J/(g \\, \\text{\u00b0C})$!$, and the latent heat of vaporization of water is $!$2260 \\, J/g$!$. (Note: $!$1 \\, kg = 1000 \\, g$!$.)",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "5487676380a6476abb372",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by selecting the correct formula to compute the mass of the water from its volume and density. Which of the following formulas correctly relates mass (m), density (\u03c1), and volume (V)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$m = \\rho \\times V$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$m = \\frac{V}{\\rho}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$m = \\rho + V$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "1f234ba74db644b0982c5",
                    "stepText": "Now, use the formula you selected along with the given values: a volume of $!$1.5$!$ L and a density of $!$1 \\text{ kg/L}$!$. Remember to convert the mass from kilograms to grams (using $!$1 \\text{ kg} = 1000 \\text{ g}$!$). What is the mass of the water in grams?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1500"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "g",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "f35921faebac45c6a0787",
                    "stepText": "Great! Next, identify the proper formula to calculate the energy required to heat water. This formula should involve the mass (m), specific heat capacity (c), and the temperature change (\\(\\Delta T\\)). Which option correctly represents this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = m \\times c \\times \\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = \\frac{m}{c \\times \\Delta T}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = c \\times \\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "438f6b24a8fb48cf9a910",
                    "stepText": "Using the heating formula from the previous step, calculate the energy required to raise the temperature of the water from $!$25^\\text{o}C$!$ to $!$100^\\text{o}C$!$. Use the mass from Step 2 ($!$1500$!$ g), the specific heat capacity $!$4.18 \\text{ J/(g \\cdot \u00b0C)}$!$, and note that the temperature change \\(\\Delta T\\) is $!$(100 - 25)$!$ \u00b0C. What is the heating energy (Q\u2081) in joules?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "470250"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "97636e23afc24b7092e28",
                    "stepText": "Now, select the correct formula for determining the energy required to convert boiling water into steam (phase change) using the latent heat of vaporization. Which of these formulas is correct?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = m \\times L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = \\frac{L}{m}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = m + L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "d4cd3aae61334ed29cfbf",
                    "stepText": "Using the formula from Step 5, calculate the energy needed to vaporize the water. Use the mass from Step 2 ($!$1500$!$ g) and the latent heat of vaporization $!$2260 \\text{ J/g}$!$. What is the vaporization energy (Q\u2082) in joules?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3390000"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "071dca367d064bbf8c298",
                    "stepText": "Finally, choose the appropriate method to combine the energies calculated in Steps 4 and 6 to find the total energy required for both heating and vaporizing the water. Which formula correctly represents this total energy?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
