        {
            "id": "dd2c3d76b48740819320b",
            "questionText": "During a long summer drive, the air inside your car tires heats up significantly, causing the kinetic energy of the gas particles to increase and leading to more frequent and forceful collisions with the tire walls. An initially inflated car tire has a pressure of $!$2.0\\,\\text{atm}$!$ when the ambient temperature is $!$27^\\circ\\text{C}$!$. After driving, the tire temperature rises to $!$57^\\circ\\text{C}$!$. Assuming the volume of the tire remains constant, calculate the new pressure of the air inside the tire in $!$\\text{atm}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "a8b41192c0e84b62baa33",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by recalling the law that relates pressure and temperature at constant volume. Please select the correct formula that describes this relationship.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2adfd026-0718-4727-9c26-9492969f7ec0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p \\propto T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V \\propto T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$pV = \\text{constant}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "3364b18a3168415a901ed",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, convert the initial temperature from Celsius to Kelvin. Remember that you can convert by adding 273 to the Celsius temperature. Calculate the Kelvin temperature for 27\u00b0C.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "300"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "12b0701c201b48c6aafd0",
                    "stepText": "Now, convert the final temperature from Celsius to Kelvin using the same conversion method. What is the Kelvin temperature for 57\u00b0C?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "330"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "a582627a68164de3b760c",
                    "stepText": "With the temperatures in Kelvin and knowing that pressure is directly proportional to temperature at constant volume, identify the correct rearranged formula to compute the new pressure. Which of the following formulas should you use?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2adfd026-0718-4727-9c26-9492969f7ec0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p_2=p_1\\times\\left(\\frac{T_2}{T_1}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p_2=\\frac{p_1\\times T_1}{T_2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p_2=\\frac{T_2}{p_1\\times T_1}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "ed628986646640c8a3aa2",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the rearranged formula and the values provided ($!$p_1=2.0\\,\\text{atm}$!$, $!$T_1=300\\,K$!$, $!$T_2=330\\,K$!$), perform the calculation to determine the new pressure inside the tire.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2.2"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "atm",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2adfd026-0718-4727-9c26-9492969f7ec0"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
